1210":"1210","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1203–":"about 1203–Deceased","1200–1258":"1200–1258","1203–Female":"1203–Deceased","1203–Male":"1203–Deceased","1205–1293":"1205–1293","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1189–1272":"1189–1272","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1175–1223":"1175–1223","1165–1235":"1165–1235","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","Abt 1203":"about 1203","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","1205":"1205","1203":"1203","1258":"1258","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","Abt 1220":"about 1220","1210":"1210","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harcourt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the places in Eure and Calvados named Harcourt, from Old French <i>cour(t)</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ) with an obscure first element. This surname is very rare in France.","English: habitational name from either of two places in Shropshire named Harcourt. The one near Cleobury Mortimer gets the name from Old English <i>heafocere</i> ‘hawker, falconer’ + <i>cot</i> ‘hut, cottage’; the one near Wem has as its first element Old English <i>hearpere</i> (see   Harper  ).","History: The surname of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with the equally rare or even extinct variants or altered forms <i>Haraucourt</i>, <i>Herancourt</i>, and <i>Héraucourt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Court","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>curt</i>, <i>court</i> ‘large house’ (a word of the same ultimately Latin origin as 2 below), denoting someone who lived or worked in a manor house or castle, a courtly retainer.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’).","English and French: nickname for a physically small man, or ironically for a large man, from the adjective Middle English <i>curt</i>, Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘short, small’ (from Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘curtailed, truncated, cut short, broken off’). Compare French   Lecourt  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Matilda</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilde de Harcourt was born about 1203, in Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Harcourt Governor of Tamworth Castle, was 29 and her mother, Alice Noell, was 39. She married Giles de Peniston. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1203–":"umbes 1203–Surnud","1200–1258":"1200–1258","1203–Female":"1203–Surnud","1203–Male":"1203–Surnud","1205–1293":"1205–1293","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1189–1272":"1189–1272","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1175–1223":"1175–1223","1165–1235":"1165–1235","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","Abt 1203":"umbes 1203","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","1205":"1205","1203":"1203","1258":"1258","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1210":"1210","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1203–":"noin 1203–Kuollut","1200–1258":"1200–1258","1203–Female":"1203–Kuollut","1203–Male":"1203–Kuollut","1205–1293":"1205–1293","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1189–1272":"1189–1272","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1175–1223":"1175–1223","1165–1235":"1165–1235","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","Abt 1203":"noin 1203","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","1205":"1205","1203":"1203","1258":"1258","1202":"1202","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","Abt 1220":"noin 1220","1210":"1210","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","S